# Environmental Requirements

## 6.1 Overview

This section defines the environmental conditions that Lunar Opensource Rover (LOR) platforms and components must withstand during lunar surface operations. All LOR-compliant systems shall be designed and tested to operate reliably under these conditions.

## 6.2 Thermal Environment

### 6.2.1 Operating Temperature Range
- **Nominal Operating Range**: -173°C to +127°C (-279°F to +261°F)
- **Survival Range**: -190°C to +150°C (-310°F to +302°F)
- **Temperature Cycling**: Systems must withstand thermal cycling between operational extremes

### 6.2.2 Thermal Design Requirements
- **Thermal Control System**: Active or passive thermal management required
- **Material Selection**: Materials must maintain structural integrity across temperature range
- **Component Derating**: Electronic components shall be derated for extreme temperature operation
- **Thermal Interface**: Standardized thermal interface points for heat dissipation

## 6.3 Radiation Environment

### 6.3.1 Radiation Exposure
- **Galactic Cosmic Rays (GCR)**: Continuous exposure to high-energy particles
- **Solar Particle Events (SPE)**: Periodic high-flux proton events
- **Total Ionizing Dose (TID)**: Minimum 100 krad tolerance for 1-year mission
- **Single Event Effects (SEE)**: Electronics must be hardened against latch-up and upset

### 6.3.2 Shielding Requirements
- **Critical Electronics**: Minimum 2mm aluminum equivalent shielding
- **Data Storage**: Radiation-tolerant memory with error correction
- **Processor Architecture**: Fault-tolerant computing with redundancy options

## 6.4 Vacuum Environment

### 6.4.1 Pressure Conditions
- **Operational Pressure**: <10⁻⁹ torr lunar surface vacuum
- **Material Outgassing**: Low outgassing materials per ASTM E595
- **Seal Requirements**: Hermetic sealing for pressurized components
- **Thermal-Vacuum Testing**: All components tested in simulated lunar vacuum

## 6.5 Mechanical Environment

### 6.5.1 Launch Environment
- **Vibration**: Random vibration per NASA-STD-7001
- **Shock**: Pyroshock and mechanical shock survival
- **Acoustic**: 140 dB overall sound pressure level
- **Acceleration**: 12g quasi-static loads in all axes

### 6.5.2 Landing Environment
- **Impact Loads**: Survive 20g deceleration during lunar landing
- **Deployment Shock**: Component release mechanism shock loads
- **Surface Operations**: Continuous low-level vibration from mobility

## 6.6 Dust Environment

### 6.6.1 Lunar Regolith Characteristics
- **Particle Size**: 0.1 to 1000 microns diameter
- **Composition**: Sharp, abrasive silicate particles
- **Electrostatic Properties**: High charging potential in vacuum
- **Adhesion**: Strong electrostatic and van der Waals forces

### 6.6.2 Dust Mitigation Requirements
- **Sealing**: IP67-equivalent sealing for mechanical interfaces
- **Materials**: Dust-resistant surface treatments and materials
- **Mechanisms**: Self-cleaning or dust-tolerant moving parts
- **Optics**: Protective covers or cleaning systems for optical surfaces

## 6.7 Electromagnetic Environment

### 6.7.1 Electromagnetic Compatibility (EMC)
- **Conducted Emissions**: Per MIL-STD-461 requirements
- **Radiated Emissions**: Minimal interference with communication systems
- **Susceptibility**: Immunity to solar radio bursts and plasma effects
- **Grounding**: Common grounding architecture for EMC compliance

### 6.7.2 Charging Environment
- **Surface Charging**: Components must survive electrostatic discharge
- **Plasma Interaction**: Operations during lunar plasma wake conditions
- **Mitigation**: Conductive paths and charge dissipation systems

## 6.8 Lighting Environment

### 6.8.1 Illumination Conditions
- **Lunar Day**: 14 Earth days of continuous sunlight
- **Lunar Night**: 14 Earth days of darkness
- **Solar Elevation**: 0° to 90° elevation angles
- **Albedo Variations**: 7-12% surface reflectance

### 6.8.2 Optical System Requirements
- **Dynamic Range**: Operate across full lunar lighting spectrum
- **Shadow Operations**: Navigation and science in permanent shadow
- **Solar Protection**: Avoid damage from direct solar observation

## 6.9 Gravity Environment

### 6.9.1 Lunar Gravity Effects
- **Surface Gravity**: 1.62 m/s² (1/6 Earth gravity)
- **Mobility Design**: Optimize traction and stability for low gravity
- **Dust Dynamics**: Modified dust settling and suspension behavior
- **Mechanical Systems**: Adjust spring rates and damping for low-g operation

## 6.10 Mission Duration Requirements

### 6.10.1 Design Life
- **Primary Mission**: Minimum 90 Earth days operational
- **Extended Mission**: Design goal of 1 Earth year
- **Survival Periods**: Withstand lunar night dormancy cycles
- **Degradation Allowance**: Performance within specifications at end of life

## 6.11 Testing and Validation

### 6.11.1 Environmental Testing Requirements
- **Thermal Vacuum**: Component and system-level thermal vacuum testing
- **Vibration Testing**: Random vibration and sine sweep testing
- **Radiation Testing**: Proton and heavy ion exposure testing
- **Dust Testing**: JSC-1A lunar simulant exposure testing

### 6.11.2 Test Standards
- **Space Environment**: NASA-HDBK-4002 space environment testing
- **Component Testing**: Per MIL-STD-810 environmental test methods
- **Materials Testing**: ASTM space materials testing standards
- **Qualification Testing**: Full qualification test program for flight hardware

## 6.12 Environmental Design Guidelines

### 6.12.1 Design Margins
- **Temperature**: ±10°C margin beyond operational requirements
- **Radiation**: 2x margin on total dose requirements
- **Mechanical**: 1.4 safety factor on ultimate loads
- **Lifetime**: 2x margin on cyclic loading requirements

### 6.12.2 Heritage and Standards
- **Space Heritage**: Utilize proven space-qualified components where possible
- **Commercial Components**: Screening and testing for commercial parts
- **Standard Compliance**: Adherence to NASA and international space standards
- **Lessons Learned**: Incorporate lunar mission heritage and lessons learned
